<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-175-194  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 175 194.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 19 1990 n578 p33(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Finding solutions is in the genes: Machine-age natural selection.andO;(Second Artificial Life Workshop)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, R. Colin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at the second semi-annual Artificial Life Workshoprevealed an electronic representation of genetics that can helpsolve engineering problems.andP;  A so called genetic algorithm mimicsthe evolution of a particular gene set in an environment.andP;  Theenvironment in such an algorithm is represented by a givenproblem, and progeny is represented by all the possible solutionsto that problem.andP;  In theory, the algorithms evolve a solution tothe problem.andP;  Rather than check all possible solutions, geneticalgorithms are designed to exploit historical information tointelligently direct a structured yet random search among allpossible solutions.andP;  The method has already been applied to VLSIlayout and compaction, recursive adaptive filter design,steady-state and transient optimization, structural optimizationand other applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Artificial Life II ConferenceAlgorithmsArtificial IntelligenceMathematical ModelsProblem Solving.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>